    sections: [
      { heading: "Vehicles and Drivers", body: "The fleet — whether one adapted people-carrier or several minibuses — is run on maintenance discipline: statutory compliance (MOT, tax, insurance specifying business use and passenger carriage) diaried with the same 60-day horizon as the premises registers; servicing per manufacturer schedule; daily-use walk-round checks recorded (tyres, lights, fluids, doors, wheelchair lift/ramp function, securement equipment present, first aid kit and emergency kit stocked, cleanliness to infection-control standard between users); accessibility equipment (lifts, ramps, winches) on inspection cycles per saf-034's lifting-equipment logic; and defects grounding the vehicle immediately with the alternative-transport arrangements absorbing the operational cost — a known-defective vehicle carrying residents is indefensible in every forum that would later ask. Staff cars used for work journeys with people carried are covered by the same gateway: business insurance confirmed annually, licence checks identical, vehicle roadworthiness declared, and the option always available to decline private-car use in favour of service or hired transport. Driver standards run past the licence: induction to each vehicle type driven, MiDAS or equivalent for minibuses, wheelchair-securement training hands-on and refreshed, the fitness-to-drive conversation normalised (medication changes, eyesight standards, the post-night-shift rule the service sets), and driving-standards feedback (complaints, telematics where fitted, observed practice) handled through supervision — because the person who drives residents is performing care at 50mph." },
      { heading: "Securement and the Physical Journey", body: "Wheelchair transport is this policy's zero-improvisation zone. The decision tree first: can and should the person transfer to a vehicle seat (often safer and more comfortable, with the wheelchair stowed) — assessed with moving-and-handling input — or do they travel in the chair? If in the chair: the chair must be transport-suitable (manufacturer-designated as crash-tested for occupied transport, or the journey re-planned), positioned facing forward in the designated station, secured with the four-point tie-down system to the frame's designated securement points — never to wheels, armrests, footplates or anything removable — tensioned per the system's instructions, with the occupant restrained by the vehicle-anchored or approved lap-and-diagonal belt (the chair's own postural harness positions, it does not protect in collision), headrest provision per the assessment, and powered chairs additionally powered down with control access managed. Staff sign off securement on the journey record for every wheelchair journey — the thirty-second discipline that prevents the sector's recurring tragedy. The wider physical journey gets its planning: transfers in and out assessed (the car transfer is a classic falls moment — saf-010's techniques travel), seating positions matched to needs (the hemiplegic side, the door the person can use, the escort's sightline to the person who needs watching), seatbelts for everyone adapted where needed (harnesses and buckle-guards by assessment, as comfort and safety, with the restraint-policy interface honoured where adaptations limit freedom), journey lengths matched to continence and comfort planning (breaks planned, supplies carried, dignity protected), and motion sickness, temperature and hydration managed as the clinical variables they are for frail travellers." },
      { heading: "Escorts as Mobile Care", body: "The escort role is defined as care delivered in motion, and planned accordingly. The assessment (per person, per journey type, reviewed with change) decides presence and skills: the anticoagulated faller needs an escort who can manage the post-fall protocol; the person with dysphagia needs one trained for choking response if food or drink features; the insulin-dependent traveller to a long clinic needs the hypo kit and someone competent with it; the person with dementia needs orientation, reassurance and absconding awareness; the person who cannot communicate needs, above all, a voice. For clinical appointments the escort's brief is explicit: carry the information pack (the hospital passport or equivalent — diagnoses, medications and times, allergies, baseline function and communication, what distress looks like for this person, contacts); support through waiting (the four-hour ED wait is a clinical deterioration risk for frail people — the escort escalates, hydrates, feeds within safety, and phones the service for decisions); be present in consultations where the person wishes or the assessment requires (advocating, translating between the person and the clinical machine, ensuring consent processes engage the person properly per cop-001); and bring the outcome home — documented into the care record same-day (findings, changes, follow-ups booked, medication changes reconciled through the medication policies' machinery). Family escorts are welcomed within honesty about limits: families carry love and knowledge, but where the assessment demands clinical competence or formal advocacy the service's escort goes too or instead, and the appointment nobody competent attended is rebooked rather than wasted. Escort staffing is the honesty test: rosters that cannot release an escort without collapsing the floor are an establishment problem for the workforce plan, and appointments cancelled for staffing are logged and reviewed as the care-denials they are." },
      { heading: "Outings, Third Parties and When It Goes Wrong", body: "Group outings get event-grade planning with joy as the objective: destination assessed (access, toilets including changing facilities where needed, terrain against the group's mobility, quiet refuges for those who saturate, eating arrangements against the dietary matrix — ch-003/004 travel too); ratios built from the actual attendees' needs with a floor-holder briefed at base; the kit assembled (medication in transit per the medication policies' custody rules, per-person emergency info, continence and weather supplies, first aid, charged phones, the contact-and-contingency plan); transport arranged per this policy's standards; and the day itself run with flexibility (the person who wants to leave early has a plan, the one having the time of their life gets the extra hour where the plan can flex). Third-party transport is managed at the booking: patient transport services get accurate need statements (mobility, escort, oxygen, bariatric equipment, behavioural support) because under-described bookings arrive as the wrong vehicle with the wrong crew; taxi firms are vetted onto an approved list (licensing, insurance, driver conduct expectations) with booking conventions that protect (staff book and confirm, drivers identify, no cash transactions with the person where ch-006 arrangements apply, arrival confirmations for solo travellers the assessment cleared); and volunteer drivers, where schemes operate, meet the same licence-insurance-DBS gateway as everything else. Incidents in motion run the machinery with roadside adaptations drilled in advance: collision (safety, 999, insurer and incident processes, welfare of everyone including the driver); clinical event (stop safely, respond per training, 999 with precise location, the service's on-call informed and deciding onward plans); behavioural escalation (de-escalate stopped and safe, abandon the journey without shame where continuing risks everyone — the return home is a success, not a failure); and every event and near-miss debriefed (hr-021's support where it was frightening) with the learning folded into the next journey's plan, because a transport system that learns is the difference between an incident and a pattern." },
    ],
